04397nam a22005535i 9780822391555DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20102010ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223915557 a10.1515/97808223915552doi  a(DE-B1597)552946  a(OCoLC)1159611977  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aF2848b.F566 2010 7aHIS0330002bisacsh1 aFinchelstein, Federico, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTransatlantic Fascism :bIdeology, Violence, and the Sacred in Argentina and Italy, 1919-1945 /cFederico Finchelstein. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2010] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (344 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Transnational Fascism -- t2. The Argentine Road to Fascism -- t3. Fascism Discovers the Americas -- t4. A ‘‘Christianized Fascism’’ -- t5. Debating Global Totalitarianism -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Transatlantic Fascism, Federico Finchelstein traces the intellectual and cultural connections between Argentine and Italian fascisms, showing how fascism circulates transnationally. From the early 1920s well into the Second World War, Mussolini tried to export Italian fascism to Argentina, the “most Italian” country outside of Italy. (Nearly half the country’s population was of Italian descent.) Drawing on extensive archival research on both sides of the Atlantic, Finchelstein examines Italy’s efforts to promote fascism in Argentina by distributing bribes, sending emissaries, and disseminating propaganda through film, radio, and print. He investigates how Argentina’s political culture was in turn transformed as Italian fascism was appropriated, reinterpreted, and resisted by the state and the mainstream press, as well as by the Left, the Right, and the radical Right.As Finchelstein explains, nacionalismo, the right-wing ideology that developed in Argentina, was not the wholesale imitation of Italian fascism that Mussolini wished it to be. Argentine nacionalistas conflated Catholicism and fascism, making the bold claim that their movement had a central place in God’s designs for their country. Finchelstein explores the fraught efforts of nationalistas to develop a “sacred” ideological doctrine and political program, and he scrutinizes their debates about Nazism, the Spanish Civil War, imperialism, anti-Semitism, and anticommunism. Transatlantic Fascism shows how right-wing groups constructed a distinctive Argentine fascism by appropriating some elements of the Italian model and rejecting others. It reveals the specifically local ways that a global ideology such as fascism crossed national borders.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aFascism and the Catholic ChurchzArgentinaxHistoryy20th century. 0aFascism and the Catholic ChurchzItalyxHistoryy20th century. 0aFascismzArgentinaxHistoryy20th century. 0aFascismzItalyxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / South America.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822391555zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822391555423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780822391555/original  a978-3-11-071183-7  Duke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles